e that major issues in Canada’s social system have been neglected in public policy. In order for these issues to be addressed we need to challenge the flawed public policies and the negative discourse that continue to marginalize single mothers—in terms of the opportunities in their own lives and in terms of how they are understood by other Canadians. The first-person narratives of the struggles and issues faced by low-income single mothers provide narrative richness and are augmented by introductory and concluding chapters that draw the narrative themes together and offer overarching discussion and analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSingle mothers -- Canada -- Biography. 0aSingle mothers -- Canada -- Social conditions. 0aSingle motherszCanadavBiography. 0aSingle motherszCanadaxSocial conditions. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh1 aAlcalde, Judit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCaragata, Lea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaragata, Lea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458636340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554586363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554586363/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles